******
[2] Italy (Sanremo, Liguria region): fatal
Date: Sun 7 Jan 2018
Source: Corriere Della Serra [in Italian, edited]
http://www.corriere.it/cronache/18_gennaio_07/a-sanremo-morto-morbillo-l-asl-nessun-pericolo-epidemia-4b996322-f3c7-11e7-aa70-8e209e058724.shtml


A 41-year-old man, a driver from Riviera Trasporti, died late yesterday [6 Jan 2018] at the Sanremo hospital for complications due to a measles infection. This was announced by the Asl 1 [local health authority] of Imperia [located in the region of Liguria]. The man, who had been transferred to the reanimation ward after a worsening of his general condition, would most likely have died from a pulmonary or cardiac complication from measles infection or from possible viral superinfection. Asl 1, "who joins the family in this moment of pain due to the terrible loss", has requested the diagnostic confirmation to confirm the causes of death.

During 2017, 4 cases were [determined] in Italy of death due to measles complications, which occurs in about 10 percent of cases. Epidemiological data at the national level show that mortality due to measles complications has an incidence of 0.1-0.2 percent, that is, 1 or 2 cases in 1000 infected patients. "We wish to reassure the population -- specifies the health management of the ASL -- to avoid alarm and unfounded fears. We are not in the presence of a measles epidemic: there have been some cases of this virus whose onset has no correspondence with the contextual seasonal influence peak. Measles, as confirmed by epidemiological data at the national level, is a disease that, if it does not present complications, can be treated at home with rest and symptomatic therapy.

According to the World Health Organization (WHO) statistics, Italy remains one of the countries most exposed to measles cases. In 2017 it was the 5th country in terms of number of patients, after India, Nigeria, Pakistan, and China.

--
Communicated by:
Remigio Russo
Professional journalist
<remigiorusso@tin.it>

[ProMED thanks Remigio Russo for submitting this report.

According to the most recent Surveillance Report of the ECDC [European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control. Monthly measles and rubella monitoring report, December 2017. Stockholm: ECDC; 2017], reporting on cases from 1 Nov 2016-31 Oct 2017, 30 EU/EEA Member States reported 13 726 cases of measles (source: TESSy [the European Surveillance System]). 29 Member States reported consistently throughout this period (Croatia did not report for October 2017). All EU/EEA countries have reported measles cases in the last 12 months, except Latvia and Malta. The number of measles cases reported to TESSy may represent an underestimation, in particular for Romania. The ongoing outbreak in the country has caused delays in case-based reporting to ECDC and the most up-to-date data are available from the Romanian National Institute of Public Health. ECDC also published a Rapid Risk Assessment on the outbreak in Romania.

During the period from 1 Nov 2016, to 31 Oct 2017, the highest numbers of cases were reported by Romania (5 605), Italy (4 973) and Germany (952), accounting for 41 percent, 36 percent, and 7 percent respectively of all cases reported by EU/EEA countries. The diagnosis of measles was confirmed by positive laboratory results (serology, virus detection, or isolation) in 61 percent of all cases reported by EU/EEA countries. The number of cases by month and notification rate per million population by country for this 12-month period is presented in Table 1. Figure 2 shows the notification rate per million population by country for this period.

See https://ecdc.europa.eu/sites/portal/files/documents/Monthly-Measles-Rubella-monitoring-report-December-2017_0.pdf for tables and figures. - Mod.LK

