South America
---
[3] Venezuela
Date: Sun 7 Jan 2018 01:15 AM VET
Source: El Nacional [in Spanish trans Mod.LK, edited]
http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/salud/sarampion-tiene-tres-semanas-caracas_217873


Since 22 Dec 2017, 10 cases with clinical and epidemiological suspicions of measles have been reported, of which 4 have already been confirmed by the Instituto Nacional de Higiene Rafael Rangel.

The Network in Defense of Epidemiology pointed out that the cases come from Valles del Tuy [several municipalities in Miranda state] and the Sucre parish [Caracas, capital district]. In the JM de los Ríos Hospital, there is a confirmed case and 2 suspects from Catia [Vargas state].

On 8 Nov 2017, the Pan American Health Organization reported that they were working on a rapid response plan, in conjunction with the Ministry of Health, to vaccinate the population from 6 months to 10 years of age, as well as selective vaccination of the population 11 years and older who have had contact with suspected or confirmed cases of measles.

The 1st phase covered the states of Bolivar, Anzoátegui, Delta Amacuro, Monagas, and Sucre. However, the Ministry has not issued any pronouncements on the approach to avoid the spread of measles.

"The rapid response plan is designed to allow the country to disrupt the circulation of measles before 1 year since the 1st case was identified, and thus to preserve the endemic measles-free country and region status," reported the international agency in a press release.

Measles spread faster than the PAHO response and the ministry plan. José Félix Oletta, member of the Network in Defense of Epidemiology, criticizes that Miranda state and Caracas [Capital District] were not taken into account in the plan of action.

"We do not know the number of immunizations from 2016 onwards for the Capital District and Miranda. We have the worst scenario: lack of information, presence of the active outbreak for 3 weeks in Caracas and zero responses to the immunization plan," he warned.

Oletta warns that general 3rd and 4th level hospitals do not have enough pediatric intensive therapy beds to cope with this outbreak. Measles can bring respiratory complications, neurological manifestations such as encephalitis, otitis, and pneumonia secondary to bacteria and the viral infections.

[Byline: Isayen Herrera]

--
Communicated by:
Kathryn Soderholm
