[ProMED thanks Kathryn Soderholm for submitting this report from ProMED-ESP.

The dire situation in Venezuela was described by B Fraser in "Data reveal state of Venezuelan health system." Lancet. 2017; 389(10084): 2095. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(17)31435-6; http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(17)31435-6/fulltext. She describes how the political and economic situation have damaged the health system in this country. "The epidemiological data show that maternal mortality rose by about 9 percent between 2014 and 2015, then jumped by nearly 66 percent by the end of 2016 -- with 756 deaths. Infant mortality rose by about 30 percent between 2015 and 2016 -- 11 466 deaths in 2016 -- according to government figures.

According to Maritza Durán, president of the Venezuelan Society of Internal Medicine, the infant mortality rate is attributable to a shortage of vaccines, basic medicines, and hospital facilities, as well as increased child malnutrition. This is a health emergency that cries out for international support. - Mod.LK

